'''Yara Belle Plaine Inc''' is a nitrate-based fertilizer manufacture based in [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]], [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]], and part of the [[Yara International]] group of companies.
Originally the company was established in 1984 as '''SaskFerco Products Inc.''', a joint venture between [[Cargil]] (50%), the Government of Saskatchewan (49%), [[Citibank Canada]] (1%), to construct a plant near [[Belle Plaine, Saskatchewan]] at a cost of $435 million for the production of [[urea|granular urea]] and [[anhydrous ammonia]].<ref name=EofS>{{cite web |url=http://esask.uregina.ca/entry/saskferco_products_inc.html |title =SASKFERCO PRODUCTS INC. |work =Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan |publisher =[[University of Regina]] |accessdate = 2011-03-20}}</ref> SaskFerco became one of the largest North America manufacturers of granular urea (2,850 tonnes per day capacity) and anhydrous ammonia (1,860 tonnes per day) and urea ammonium nitrate (670 tonnes per day). <ref name=EofS/> The plant also became the largest consumer of [[natural gas]] in the province.<ref name=EofS/>
In 2008 the company was sold by the province and its partner at that time [[The Mosaic Company]] to [[Yara International]] for $1.6 billion; the name of the company was changed to '''Yara Belle Plaine Inc,''' and it continued to be headquartered in Regina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.sk.ca/news?newsId=a200a881-a02c-4671-9023-f01d7af514e2 |title =SALE OF SASKFERCO IS FINALIZED |work =Press Release |publisher =[[Investment Saskatchewan]] |accessdate = 2011-03-20}}</ref>
